{
  "id": "019d3c81-8859-7230-b665-08b19e24cb5a",
  "content": "# Embedding Storage Redb VECTORS Table -- Decision Record (2026-03-30)\n## What: Moved 768-dim embeddings from inline JSON to a dedicated Redb VECTORS table\n## Key Design Decisions:\n1. Redb VECTORS table with `TableDefinition<&[u8; 16], &[u8]>` (UUID bytes key, raw f32 bytes via bytemuck). Chosen over custom binary sidecar to eliminate ~500-1000 lines of crash-safety code.\n2. `#[serde(skip_serializing)]` on embedding field. Affects ALL serialization paths. Required companion .vec files for staging and get_embedding() on QueryableStore trait for read-then-reinsert flows (merge worker, commit pipeline).\n3. Rebuild reads from VECTORS table first, falls back to JSON for pre-migration entries.\n4. Dashboard clustering/activity restored via load_scope_entries_with_embeddings helper.\n5. GC Forgotten-tier transition cleans up VECTORS entries (prevents orphaned rows).\n## Review Findings Worth Remembering:\n- skip_serializing propagates globally. Any read-then-write flow (merge, commit, GC) must explicitly restore embeddings from VECTORS.\n- Dashboard reads JSON files directly (not through store). Must separately handle embedding enrichment.\n- bytemuck uses native endianness. Redb files not portable across architectures. Documented at VECTORS table definition.\n## What Blocked:\n- Dashboard clustering regression was not obvious until review. Required updating 3 endpoints to use VECTORS for embeddings.",
